# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: optimal-transport
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] In computer science, the **earth mover's distance** (**EMD**) is a measure of dissimilarity between two frequency distributions, densities, or measures, over a metric space *D*.
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] Over probability distributions, the earth mover's distance is also known as the Wasserstein metric $W_{1}$ , Kantorovich–Rubinstein metric, or Mallows's distance.
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] where $\Pi (P,Q)$ is the set of all joint distributions whose marginals are P and Q .
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] where the supremum is taken over all 1-Lipschitz continuous functions, i.e. $\|\nabla f(x)\|\leq 1\quad \forall x$ .
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] In some applications, it is convenient to represent a distribution ${\textstyle P}$ as a *signature*, or a collection of *clusters*, where the ${\textstyle i}$ -th cluster represents a feature of mass ${\textstyle w_{i}}$ centered at ${\textstyle p_{i}}$ .
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] Let ${\textstyle D=[d_{i,j}]}$ be the ground distance between clusters ${\textstyle p_{i}}$ and ${\textstyle q_{j}}$ .
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] Then the EMD between ${\textstyle P}$ and ${\textstyle Q}$ is given by the optimal flow ${\textstyle F=[f_{i,j}]}$ , with ${\textstyle f_{i,j}}$ the flow between ${\textstyle p_{i}}$ and ${\textstyle q_{j}}$ , that minimizes the overall cost.
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] The optimal flow ${\textstyle F}$ is found by solving this linear optimization problem.
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] Some applications may require the comparison of distributions with different total masses.
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] One approach is to allow for *partial matching*, where dirt from the more massive distribution is rearranged to make the less massive, and any leftover "dirt" is discarded at no cost.
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] Formally, let ${\textstyle w_{P}}$ be the total weight of ${\textstyle P}$ , and ${\textstyle w_{Q}}$ be the total weight of ${\textstyle Q}$ .
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] where $\Pi _{\geq }(P,Q)$ is the set of all measures whose projections are $\geq P$ and $\geq Q$ .
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] Note that this generalization of EMD is not a true distance between distributions, as it does not satisfy the triangle inequality.
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] An alternative approach is to allow for mass to be created or destroyed, on a global or local level, as an alternative to transportation, but with a cost penalty.
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] In that case one must specify a real parameter $\alpha$ , the ratio between the cost of creating or destroying one unit of "dirt", and the cost of transporting it by a unit distance.
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] This is equivalent to minimizing the sum of the earth moving cost plus $\alpha$ times the *L*1 distance between the rearranged pile and the second distribution.
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] The resulting measure ${\widehat {EMD}}_{\alpha }$ is a true distance function.
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] The EMD can be extended naturally to the case where more than two distributions are compared.
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] In this case, the "distance" between the many distributions is defined as the optimal value of a linear program.
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] This generalized EMD may be computed exactly using a greedy algorithm, and the resulting functional has been shown to be Minkowski additive and convex monotone.
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] The EMD can be computed by solving an instance of transportation problem, using any algorithm for minimum-cost flow problem, e.g. the network simplex algorithm.
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] The Hungarian algorithm can be used to get the solution if the domain *D* is the set {0, 1}.
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] If the domain is integral, it can be translated for the same algorithm by representing integral bins as multiple binary bins.
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] As a special case, if *D* is a one-dimensional array of "bins" of length *n*, the EMD can be efficiently computed by scanning the array and keeping track of how much dirt needs to be transported between consecutive bins.
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] EMD-based similarity analysis (EMDSA) is an important and effective tool in many multimedia information retrieval and pattern recognition applications.
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] However, the computational cost of EMD is super-cubic to the number of the "bins" given an arbitrary "D".
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] Efficient and scalable EMD computation techniques for large scale data have been investigated using MapReduce, as well as bulk synchronous parallel and resilient distributed dataset.
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] An early application of the EMD in computer science was to compare two grayscale images that may differ due to dithering, blurring, or local deformations.
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] In this case, the region is the image's domain, and the total amount of light (or ink) is the "dirt" to be rearranged.
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] The EMD is widely used in content-based image retrieval to compute distances between the color histograms of two digital images.
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] In this case, the region is the RGB color cube, and each image pixel is a parcel of "dirt".
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] The same technique can be used for any other quantitative pixel attribute, such as luminance, gradient, apparent motion in a video frame, etc..
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] More generally, the EMD is used in pattern recognition to compare generic summaries or surrogates of data records called signatures.
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] A typical signature consists of list of pairs ((*x*1,*m*1), ...
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] (*x**n*,*m**n*)), where each *x**i* is a certain "feature" (e.g., color in an image, letter in a text, etc.), and *m**i* is "mass" (how many times that feature occurs in the record).
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] Alternatively, *x**i* may be the centroid of a data cluster, and *m**i* the number of entities in that cluster.
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] To compare two such signatures with the EMD, one must define a distance between features, which is interpreted as the cost of turning a unit mass of one feature into a unit mass of the other.
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] The EMD between two signatures is then the minimum cost of turning one of them into the other.
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] EMD analysis has been used for quantitating multivariate changes in biomarkers measured by flow cytometry, with potential applications to other technologies that report distributions of measurements.
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] The concept was first introduced by Gaspard Monge in 1781, in the context of transportation theory.
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] The use of the EMD as a distance measure for monochromatic images was described in 1989 by S.
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] The name "earth mover's distance" was proposed by J.
[src:optimal-transport/earth-mover-s-distance] Stolfi in 1994, and was used in print in 1998 by Y.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] In mathematics, the **Wasserstein distance** or **Kantorovich–Rubinstein metric** is a distance function defined between probability distributions on a given metric space M .
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Intuitively, if each distribution is viewed as a unit amount of earth (soil) piled on *M*, the metric is the minimum "cost" of turning one pile into the other, which is assumed to be the amount of earth that needs to be moved times the mean distance it has to be moved.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] This problem was first formalised by Gaspard Monge in 1781.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Because of this analogy, the metric is known in computer science as the earth mover's distance.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Let $(M,d)$ be a metric space that is a Polish space.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Here, a coupling $\gamma$ is a joint probability measure on $M\times M$ whose marginals are $\mu$ and $\nu$ on the first and second factors, respectively.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] This means that for all measurable $A\subset M$ , it fulfills $\gamma (A\times M)=\mu (A)$ and $\gamma (M\times A)=\nu (A)$ .
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] The metric space (***P***∞(*M*), *W*∞) is complete if (*M*, *d*) is separable and complete.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Here, ***P***∞ is the space of all probability measures with bounded support.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] The name "Wasserstein distance" was coined by R.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Dobrushin in 1970, after learning of it in the work of Leonid Vaseršteĭn on Markov processes describing large systems of automata (Russian, 1969).
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] However the metric was first defined by Leonid Kantorovich in *The Mathematical Method of Production Planning and Organization* (Russian original 1939) in the context of optimal transport planning of goods and materials.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Some scholars thus encourage use of the terms "Kantorovich metric" and "Kantorovich distance".
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Most English-language publications use the German spelling "Wasserstein" (attributed to the name "Vaseršteĭn" (Russian: Васерштейн) being of Yiddish origin).
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] One way to understand the above definition is to consider the optimal transport problem.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] That is, for a distribution of mass $\mu (x)$ on a space X , we wish to transport the mass in such a way that it is transformed into the distribution $\nu (x)$ on the same space; transforming the 'pile of earth' $\mu$ to the pile $\nu$ .
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] This problem only makes sense if the pile to be created has the same mass as the pile to be moved; therefore without loss of generality assume that $\mu$ and $\nu$ are probability distributions containing a total mass of 1.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] that gives the cost of transporting a unit mass from the point x to the point y .
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] A transport plan to move $\mu$ into $\nu$ can be described by a function $\gamma (x,y)$ which gives the amount of mass to move from x to y .
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] You can imagine the task as the need to move a pile of earth of shape $\mu$ to the hole in the ground of shape $\nu$ such that at the end, both the pile of earth and the hole in the ground completely vanish.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] That is, that the total mass moved *out of* an infinitesimal region around x must be equal to $\mu (x)\mathrm {d} x$ and the total mass moved *into* a region around y must be $\nu (y)\mathrm {d} y$ .
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] This is equivalent to the requirement that $\gamma$ be a joint probability distribution with marginals $\mu$ and $\nu$ .
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Thus, the infinitesimal mass transported from x to y is $\gamma (x,y)\,\mathrm {d} x\,\mathrm {d} y$ , and the cost of moving is $c(x,y)\gamma (x,y)\,\mathrm {d} x\,\mathrm {d} y$ , following the definition of the cost function.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] The plan $\gamma$ is not unique; the optimal transport plan is the plan with the minimal cost out of all possible transport plans.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Gaspard Monge, who first considered the problem, considered it as an abstraction of a practical problem.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Monge studied descriptive geometry in the context of military fortification.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] At the time, the outer walls were built with a large amount of earth which would be costly to transport.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Furthermore, the ground near the outer walls would also be shaped with structures like ditches to remove favorable attacking positions.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] The military engineer, during design, should design it according to the terrain, so that for each sector of the fortress, the volume of the *déblai* (the earth excavated) would approximately equal the *remblai* (the material which built up the body of the rampart).
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Monge abstracted the problem of minimizing transport cost between the *déblai* and *remblai* into a problem in pure geometry, and published it as *Mémoire sur la Théorie des Déblais et des Remblais*.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Point masses naturally arise in statistics.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] If P and Q are empirical distributions, each based on n observations, then $W_{p}(P,Q)=\inf _{\pi }\left({\frac {1}{n}}\sum _{i=1}^{n}\|X_{i}-Y_{\pi (i)}\|^{p}\right)^{\frac {1}{p}},$ where the infimum is over all permutations $\pi$ of n elements.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] This is a linear assignment problem, and can be solved by the Hungarian algorithm in cubic time.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Note that the second term (involving the trace) is precisely the (unnormalised) Bures metric between $C_{1}$ and $C_{2}$ .
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Let $\mu _{1},\mu _{2}\in P_{p}(\mathbb {R} )$ be probability measures on $\mathbb {R}$ , and denote their cumulative distribution functions by $F_{1}(x)$ and $F_{2}(x)$ .
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Then the transport problem has an analytic solution: Optimal transport preserves the order of probability mass elements, so the mass at quantile q of $\mu _{1}$ moves to quantile q of $\mu _{2}$ .
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Convergence with respect to *W**p* is equivalent to the usual weak convergence of measures plus convergence of the first *p*th moments.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] For any *p* ≥ 1, the metric space (***P****p*(*M*), *W**p*) is separable, and is complete if (*M*, *d*) is separable and complete.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] By a theorem of Gangbo and McCann, if $X,Y$ are subsets of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , and the cost function $c(x,y)=h(x-y)$ for some strictly convex function $h:\mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \mathbb {R}$ , then the optimal transport problem has a unique optimal transport map.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] In particular, for all $p>1$ , optimal transport map exists and is unique.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Kantorovich and Rubinstein proved a duality representation theorem for general cost functions $c(x,y)$ , of which the Wasserstein metric is a special case.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Given a cost function $c(x,y)$ , it produces a duality transformation $\psi \mapsto \psi ^{c}$ defined by $\psi ^{c}(y):=\inf _{x}(c(x,y)-\psi (x))$ This generalizes Legendre transformation, which is the case where $c(x,y)=xy$ with a sign flip.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] We say that a function $\psi$ is ***c*-convex** iff $\psi =\varphi ^{c}$ for some $\varphi$ .
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Like in the case of convex transformation, a function is *c*-convex iff its double dual is itself.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] The following is an intuitive proof which skips over technical points.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] That is, the problem pair exhibits *strong duality*.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] For the general case, the dual problem is found by converting sums to integrals: ${\begin{cases}\sup _{f,g}\mathbb {E} _{x\sim \mu }[f(x)]+\mathbb {E} _{y\sim \nu }[g(y)]\\[6pt]f(x)+g(y)\leq c(x,y)\end{cases}}$ and the *strong duality* still holds.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] This is the **Kantorovich duality theorem**.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Start with $W_{1}(\mu ,\nu )=\sup _{f(x)+g(y)\leq d(x,y)}\mathbb {E} _{x\sim \mu }[f(x)]+\mathbb {E} _{y\sim \nu }[g(y)].$ Then, for any choice of g , one can push the term higher by setting $f(x)=\inf _{y}d(x,y)-g(y)$ , making it an infimal convolution of $-g$ with a cone.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] The two infimal convolution steps are visually clear when the probability space is $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] For notational convenience, let $\square$ denote the infimal convolution operation.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] For the first step, where we used $f={\text{cone}}\mathbin {\square } (-g)$ , plot out the curve of $-g$ , then at each point, draw a cone of slope 1, and take the lower envelope of the cones as f , as shown in the diagram, then f cannot increase with slope larger than 1.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] For the second step, picture the infimal convolution ${\text{cone}}\mathbin {\square } (-f)$ , then if all secants of f have slope at most 1, then the lower envelope of ${\text{cone}}\mathbin {\square } (-f)$ are just the cone-apices themselves, thus ${\text{cone}}\mathbin {\square } (-f)=-f$ .
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] In the case of *W*1, we have $c(x,y)=d(x,y)$ , and there is a particularly simple way to state that a function is c-convex in this case: a function f is *c*-convex iff it is Lipschitz, with Lipschitz constant $\leq 1$ .
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] In this case, $f^{c}=-f$ , so the Kantorovich duality states that $W_{1}(\mu ,\nu )=\sup \left\{\left.\int _{M}f(x)\,\mathrm {d} (\mu -\nu )(x)\,\right|{\text{ continuous }}f:M\to \mathbb {R} ,\operatorname {Lip} (f)\leq 1\right\},$ This form shows that *W*1 is an integral probability metric.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] If there exists a f that reaches the supremum exactly, then such a function is called a **Kantorovich potential** for this optimal transport problem.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] For example, for any $k>2$ , the optimal transport plan of moving an upside-down unit hemisphere centered at $(0,0,k)$ to a rightside-up unit hemisphere centered at $(0,0,0)$ is simply moving it along the *z*-direction.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] This is proven by using the Kantorovich potential $f(x,y,z)=z$ .
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Monge's original insight was that, in the case where X is a Riemannian manifold with the geodesic distance metric, the duality of optimal transport is geometrically meaningful.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Let $\gamma$ be an optimal transport plan from $\mu$ to $\nu$ .
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] To avoid complications and make the imagery clear, suppose that $\gamma$ is a *deterministic* plan.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] That is, it is equivalent to a transport *map* $T:\operatorname {supp} (\mu )\to \operatorname {supp} (\nu )$ , so that any infinitesimal lump of coal at x is transported to $T(x)$ .
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] The entire transport map can then be drawn as a family of geodesic curve segments in X connecting each x to its corresponding $T(x)$ .
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Monge noted that the transport rays do not intersect at an angle, because otherwise the plan is not optimal.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Concretely, suppose that there exist $x,x'$ such that $x\to T(x)$ and $x'\to T(x')$ intersect at an X-shape at some point y , then we can redirect x to $T(x')$ and vice versa, and "pull apart" the X-shape into a )(-shape, and thus cost less in transport.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Therefore, the transport rays make up a non-intersecting family of geodesic arcs.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Monge studied first the case where $X=\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ , in which case transport rays are line segments.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] He studied in particular the case where the transport rays cover a solid region of the plane.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] That is, we have a 1-parameter family of lines, a **line congruence**.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] He showed that these are orthogonal to a 1-parameter family of curves.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] That is, there exists some partially defined $f:\mathbb {R} ^{2}\to \mathbb {R}$ , such that each contour curve $f^{-1}(k)$ is orthogonal to the transport rays, and furthermore, the curves are separated by their distance.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] That is, starting on some point z on the curve $f^{-1}(k)$ , and move along the transport ray that the point z is on for a distance $\delta k$ , we would arrive at a point on the curve $f^{-1}(k+\delta k)$ .
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Any point in the thin slice can be moved to any other point in the other thin slice without changing the cost.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Furthermore, any other plan is suboptimal.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] In this way, the Kantorovich potential field entirely solves the problem.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Each line in the line congruence divides the plane into two halves, such that the mass of $\mu ,\nu$ in the two halves are the same.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] The line congruence produces a caustic curve, and the involutes of the caustic curve are the contours of the Kantorovich potential field.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Next, Monge noted that when $X=\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ , transport rays are line segments.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] He studied in particular the case where the transport rays cover a solid region of space.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] That is, we have a 2-parameter line congruence.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] He showed that these are orthogonal to a 1-parameter family of surfaces.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] That is, there exists some partially defined $f:\mathbb {R} ^{3}\to \mathbb {R}$ , such that each contour surface $f^{-1}(k)$ is orthogonal to the transport rays, and furthermore, the surfaces are separated by their distance.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] That is, starting on some point z on the surface $f^{-1}(k)$ , and move along the transport ray that the point z is on for a distance $\delta k$ , we would arrive at a point on the surface $f^{-1}(k+\delta k)$ .
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Any infinitesimal circle in the transport rays sweeps out a thin tube in space, and it encloses one thin filament in $\mu$ and another in $\nu$ .
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Any point in one thin filament can slide along the tube to any other point in the other thin filament without changing the cost.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Unlike the planar case, a non-intersecting family of line congruences cannot in general be normal to any surface.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] For example, consider the standard contact structure on $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ , which can be understood as a field of infinitesimal planes.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Now, perpendicular to every infinitesimal plane, draw a directed ray.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] This gives us a "twisted" line congruence.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] There is no surface perpendicular to the congruence, because there is no surface that can be tangent to every infinitesimal plane.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] However, Monge showed that in this particular case, this 2-parameter line congruence can be split into a 1-parameter family of 1-parameter line congruences, in such a way that each such 1-parameter line congruence is a developable surface.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Thus, the 2-parameter line congruence is generated as the grid of intersections between two 1-parameter families of developable surfaces.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] He showed that a line congruence satisfying such a condition *is* normal to a 1-parameter family of surfaces, and thus he constructed the surfaces.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] In modern language, he showed that this is an *integrable* foliation of space by lines.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Each contour surface $f^{-1}(k)$ intersects these two families of developable surfaces at two families of curves, and Monge named them "lines of curvature".
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] He would later study those of the ellipsoid in 1795.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Let the surfaces be contours of the equation $f(x,y,z)=const$ .
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] The lines of curvature can be computed from the equation, and 4 lines of curvature produce an infinitesimal square tube.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] The volumes of $\mu$ and $\nu$ cut by the square tube are equal.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] This is the partial differential equation satisfied by the surface.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] In general, at each point z on a transport ray $x\to T(x)$ , define the unit velocity vector $v_{z}$ .
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] The vector field cannot have curl in it, since if there is a curl, then effectively, some lump of coal is being transported in a cycle, which is suboptimal.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Therefore, the vector field is irrotational, thus locally integrable as the gradient field $\nabla f$ of some function $X\to \mathbb {R}$ .
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] This corresponds to the general fact that an optimal transport plan is *c*-cyclically monotonic.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] In this way, an optimal transport map produces the Kantorovich potential.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Note that in general, the Kantorovich potential is not everywhere differentiable, and there may be singular points on its surface.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] For example, consider the transport from the unit circle in $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ to the origin.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Its optimal transport rays are radii of the circle, and its Kantorovich potential has a sharp point at origin.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] However, it is still differentiable generically, i.e. almost everywhere (like in Sard's theorem).
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Conversely, given a continuous $f:X\to \mathbb {R}$ such that almost everywhere it is differentiable with gradient $\nabla f$ of unit length, it is a Kantorovich potential, and its gradient flow generates an optimal transport map.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] This duality between the transport *rays* and the potential *field* can be regarded as a Huygens–Fresnel principle.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Economically, this can be interpreted as follows.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] The price of coal vary over space, so define the price function $f:X\to \mathbb {R}$ , where $f(x)$ is the price of coal at location x .
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] The market may have opportunity for spatial arbitrage, means that $\exists x,x'\in X$ such that $f(x)-f(x')>d(x,x')$ .
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] An enterprising merchant can then buy coal at $x'$ and sell coal at x , earning a net profit of $f(x)-f(x')-d(x,x')$ .
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] The price function is *c*-convex iff it is free of spatial arbitrage.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] For example, a market of constant pricing $f=c_{0}$ has no spatial arbitrage, since the coal is the same price everywhere, so any movement of coal would waste transportation without earning any profit.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Given such a market, a configuration of coal $\mu$ has a total market-value of $\int _{X}fd\mu$ , and two configurations $\mu ,\nu$ may have differing market-values $\int _{X}fd(\mu -\nu )$ .
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] The shadow price interpretation is Kantorovich's original understanding of the duality between optimal planning and market pricing.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Suppose $\mu ,\nu$ are distributions on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ with probability density functions $\rho _{\mu },\rho _{\nu }$ .
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] In this case, a map $T:\operatorname {supp} (\mu )\to \operatorname {supp} (\nu )$ is a transport map iff it satisfies $\int h(T(x))\rho _{\mu }(x)dx=\int h(y)\rho _{\nu }(y)dy$ for any integrable test function $h\in L^{1}(\operatorname {supp} (\nu ))$ .
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] By a theorem of Brenier, the optimal transport map is the (almost everywhere) unique gradient of a convex function $u:\operatorname {supp} (\mu )\to \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , with $T=\nabla \psi$ .
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Conversely, some Monge–Ampère equations can be interpreted optimal transport.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Weak-solutions of a Monge–Ampère equations obtained by optimal transport are often called **Brenier solutions** in the literature.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Brenier solutions satisfy their corresponding Monge–Ampère equations almost everywhere.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] This connection to the Monge–Ampère equation allows one to apply regularity theory to optimal transport with quadratic cost.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] At this point, a very short proof of the **isoperimetric inequality** appears.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] The inequality states that among all open sets of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ with smooth boundaries, the sphere has the smallest surface area (after scaling).
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Consider the quadratic cost transport problem from the uniform distribution on X to the uniform distribution on $B_{1}$ .
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] By the regularity theory of optimal transport, there exists some convex u , smooth on all of X , such that $T:X\to B_{1}$ defined by $T=\nabla u$ is a transport map.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Then we have the following properties: ${\begin{cases}|T|\leq 1\\\det(DT)={\frac {|B_{1}|}{X}}\\\operatorname {div} (T)\geq n\det(DT)^{1/n}\end{cases}}$ The first two properties are because T is a transport map.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] The third property is by first noting that the convexity of u implies all eigenvalues of $DT$ are nonnegative, then applying the AM–GM inequality.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Angenent, Haker, and Tannenbaum proposed a way to obtain the optimal transport map by minimizing flow.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Benamou & Brenier found a dual representation of $W_{2}$ by fluid mechanics, which allows efficient solution by convex optimization.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] Under suitable assumptions, $W_{2}$ is Lipschitz-equivalent to a negative-order homogeneous Sobolev norm.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] The Wasserstein metric is a natural way to compare the probability distributions of two variables *X* and *Y*, where one variable is derived from the other by small, non-uniform perturbations (random or deterministic).
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] In computer science, for example, the metric *W*1 is widely used to compare discrete distributions, *e.g.* the color histograms of two digital images; see earth mover's distance for more details.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] In their paper 'Wasserstein GAN', Arjovsky et al. use the Wasserstein-1 metric as a way to improve the original framework of generative adversarial networks (GAN), to alleviate the vanishing gradient and the mode collapse issues.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] The special case of normal distributions is used in a Frechet inception distance.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] The Wasserstein metric has a formal link with Procrustes analysis, with application to chirality measures, and to shape analysis.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] In applied and computational topology, the Wasserstein metric can be used to compare persistence diagrams, for example cytometry datasets in computational biology.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] The Wasserstein metric also has been used in inverse problems in geophysics.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] The Wasserstein metric is used in integrated information theory to compute the difference between concepts and conceptual structures.
[src:optimal-transport/kantorovich-metric] The Wasserstein metric and related formulations have also been used to provide a unified theory for shape observable analysis in high energy and collider physics datasets.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] In mathematics and economics, **transportation theory** or **transport theory** is a name given to the study of optimal transportation and allocation of resources.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] The problem was formalized by the French mathematician Gaspard Monge in 1781.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] Tolstoi was one of the first to study the transportation problem mathematically.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] In 1930, in the collection *Transportation Planning Volume I* for the National Commissariat of Transportation of the Soviet Union, he published a paper "Methods of Finding the Minimal Kilometrage in Cargo-transportation in space".
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] Major advances were made in the field during World War II by the Soviet mathematician and economist Leonid Kantorovich.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] Consequently, the problem as it is stated is sometimes known as the **Monge–Kantorovich transportation problem**.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] The linear programming formulation of the transportation problem is also known as the Hitchcock–Koopmans transportation problem.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] Suppose that we have a collection of m mines mining iron ore, and a collection of n factories which use the iron ore that the mines produce.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] Suppose for the sake of argument that these mines and factories form two disjoint subsets M and F of the Euclidean plane $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ .
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] Suppose also that we have a *cost function* $c:\mathbb {R} ^{2}\times \mathbb {R} ^{2}\to [0,\infty )$ , so that $c(x,y)$ is the cost of transporting one shipment of iron from x to y .
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] For simplicity, we ignore the time taken to do the transporting.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] We also assume that each mine can supply only one factory (no splitting of shipments) and that each factory requires precisely one shipment to be in operation (factories cannot work at half- or double-capacity).
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] Having made the above assumptions, a *transport plan* is a bijection $T:M\to F$ .
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] In other words, each mine $m\in M$ supplies precisely one target factory $T(m)\in F$ and each factory is supplied by precisely one mine.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] is the least of all possible transport plans from M to F .
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] This motivating special case of the transportation problem is an instance of the assignment problem.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] More specifically, it is equivalent to finding a minimum weight matching in a bipartite graph.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] This can be generalized to the continuous case, where there are infinitely many mines and factories distributed on the real line, or generally in any metric space.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] This case is usually pictured as "changing the shape of a pile of dirt", and thus called the earth mover's problem.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] The following simple example illustrates the importance of the cost function in determining the optimal transport plan.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] Suppose that we have n books of equal width on a shelf (the real line), arranged in a single contiguous block.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] We wish to rearrange them into another contiguous block, but shifted one book-width to the right.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] 2. move the left-most book n book-widths to the right and leave all other books fixed ("one big move").
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] If the cost function is proportional to Euclidean distance ( $c(x,y)=\alpha \|x-y\|$ for some $\alpha >0$ ) then these two candidates are *both* optimal.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] If, on the other hand, we choose the strictly convex cost function proportional to the square of Euclidean distance ( $c(x,y)=\alpha \|x-y\|^{2}$ for some $\alpha >0$ ), then the "many small moves" option becomes the unique minimizer.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] Note that the above cost functions consider only the horizontal distance traveled by the books, not the horizontal distance traveled by a device used to pick each book up and move the book into position.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] If the latter is considered instead, then, of the two transport plans, the second is always optimal for the Euclidean distance, while, provided there are at least 3 books, the first transport plan is optimal for the squared Euclidean distance.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] The following transportation problem formulation is credited to F.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] , find a flow that satisfies demand from supplies and minimizes the flow cost.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] Tjalling Koopmans is also credited with formulations of transport economics and allocation of resources.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] The transportation problem as it is stated in modern or more technical literature looks somewhat different because of the development of Riemannian geometry and measure theory.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] The mines-factories example, simple as it is, is a useful reference point when thinking of the abstract case.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] In this setting, we allow the possibility that we may not wish to keep all mines and factories open for business, and allow mines to supply more than one factory, and factories to accept iron from more than one mine.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] Let X and Y be two separable metric spaces such that any probability measure on X (or Y ) is a Radon measure (i.e. they are Radon spaces).
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] Let $c:X\times Y\to [0,\infty )$ be a Borel-measurable function.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] where $T_{*}(\mu )$ denotes the push forward of $\mu$ by T .
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] A map T that attains this infimum (*i.e.* makes it a minimum instead of an infimum) is called an "optimal transport map".
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] Monge's formulation of the optimal transportation problem can be ill-posed, because sometimes there is no T satisfying $T_{*}(\mu )=\nu$ : this happens, for example, when $\mu$ is a Dirac measure but $\nu$ is not.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] where $\Gamma (\mu ,\nu )$ denotes the collection of all probability measures on $X\times Y$ with marginals $\mu$ on X and $\nu$ on Y .
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] Given a cost function $c(x,y)$ , it produces a duality transformation $\psi \mapsto \psi ^{c}$ defined by $\psi ^{c}(y):=\inf _{x}(c(x,y)-\psi (x))$ This generalizes Legendre transformation, which is the case where $c(x,y)=-xy$ with a sign flip.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] We say that a function $\psi$ is ***c*-convex** if $\psi =\varphi ^{c}$ for some $\varphi$ .
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] Note that because $\varphi ^{ccc}=\varphi ^{c}$ , we can always assume that $\varphi$ is *c*-convex.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] The ***c*-convexification** of a function $\psi$ is $\psi ^{cc}$ .
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] Equivalently, it is the smallest *c*-convex function $\psi '$ such that $\psi '\geq \psi$ pointwise.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] Like in the case of convex transformation, $\psi$ is *c*-convex iff $\psi =\psi ^{cc}$ .
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] If $\psi =\varphi ^{c}:X\to \mathbb {R}$ is *c*-convex, then the set of ***c*-subdifferential** of $\psi$ at $x\in X$ is the set of $y\in Y$ such that $\psi (x)=c(x,y)-\varphi (y)$ .
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] When $X=Y$ , the graph $(y,\psi ^{c}(y))$ can be constructed as follows: Take the graph of $\psi$ , and flip it upside down.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] At each point $(x,-\psi (x))$ , construct a graph of $y\mapsto c(x,y)$ apexed at $(x,-\psi (x))$ .
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] That is, it is the graph of $y\mapsto c(x,y)-\psi (x)$ .
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] Their lower-edge envelope is the graph of $\psi ^{c}$ .
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] In the same image, we can see what it means for a function $\varphi (y)$ to be *c*-convex.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] It is *c*-convex iff its entire graph can be "touched" by a "tipped tool" that is moving and shape-shifting.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] When the tipped tool is at x , it has a shape of $y\mapsto c(x,y)$ and is raised to a height of $-\psi (x)$ .
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] The graph of the *c*-convexification $\varphi ^{cc}(y)$ is constructed by running the tipped tool so that it is lowered as much as possible, while still touching graph of $\varphi (y)$ on the upper side.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] The lower envelope swept out by the tipped tool is the graph of $\varphi ^{cc}(y)$ .
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] For example, if $X=Y=\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ is a metric space and $c(x,y)=\|x-y\|$ , then $\varphi :X\to \mathbb {R}$ is *c*-convex iff it is 1-Lipschitz.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] This is used in the definition of 1-Wasserstein distance.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] If $c(x,y)=\|x-y\|^{2}$ , then $\varphi$ is *c*-convex iff its graph could be touched from above by a tipped tool with the shape of a paraboloid.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] Under fairly permissive assumptions, optimal transport plan exists.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] Note that the infimum could be infinite if all transport plans turn out to be infinite.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] A restriction of an optimal transport plan is still optimal.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] That is, suppose $\gamma \in \Gamma (\mu ,\nu )$ is optimal, and $0<\gamma '<\gamma$ , and define the normalized transport plan ${\bar {\gamma }}':=\gamma '/\gamma '(X\times Y)$ , then ${\bar {\gamma }}'$ is an optimal transport plan between its own marginals.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] If ${\bar {\gamma }}'$ isn't optimal, then there exists an improvement of it, which then translates back to an improvement of the original $\gamma$ .
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] Consider the second case, where we can actually arrive at an exactly optimal plan, instead of merely getting closer and closer.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] In this case, an optimal transport plan $\gamma \in \Gamma (\mu ,\nu )$ , constrains the form of an optimal pricing pair $(\varphi ,\psi )$ , and vice versa.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] More succinctly, a transport plan is optimal iff it is supported on the set of *c*-subdifferential pairs of $(\varphi ,\psi )$ .
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] Similarly, the optimal transport map is also stable.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] The optimal transport problem has an economic interpretation.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] In the interpretation, the duality transformation transforms a loading cost function $\varphi (x)$ into the optimal (for the shipper) unloading cost function $\psi (y)=\varphi ^{c}(y)$ .
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] If the unloading cost function $\psi (y)$ were any higher at any point, then there would be some route $x\to y$ on which $c(x,y)<\varphi (x)+\psi (y)$ , meaning that there is some route on which you would rather ship yourself.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] But if the unloading cost function were any lower at any point, then the shipper could have earned more money by raising the price there.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] Therefore, the shipper should always choose $\psi =\varphi ^{c}$ .
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] Assume that the shipper in fact must pay the same cost function and us, and can exactly reach the maximum revenue using $(\varphi ,\psi )$ as their pricing chart.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] Then the shipper must use an optimal plan, at which point the shipper just breaks even with no profit.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] Conversely, any shipping plan that allows the shipper to exactly break even must be optimal.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] For $1\leq p<\infty$ , let ${\mathcal {P}}_{p}(\mathbb {R} )$ denote the collection of probability measures on $\mathbb {R}$ that have finite p -th moment.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] The proof of this solution appears in Rachev & Rüschendorf (1998).
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] In the case where the margins $\mu$ and $\nu$ are discrete, let $\mu _{x}$ and $\nu _{y}$ be the probability masses respectively assigned to $x\in \mathbf {X}$ and $y\in \mathbf {Y}$ , and let $\gamma _{xy}$ be the probability of an $xy$ assignment.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] In order to input this in a linear programming problem, we need to vectorize the matrix $\gamma _{xy}$ by either stacking its columns or its rows, we call $\operatorname {vec}$ this operation.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] where $\otimes$ is the Kronecker product, $1_{n\times m}$ is a matrix of size $n\times m$ with all entries of ones, and $I_{n}$ is the identity matrix of size n .
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] which can be readily inputted in a large-scale linear programming solver (see chapter 3.4 of Galichon (2016)).
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] In the semi-discrete case, $X=Y=\mathbb {R} ^{d}$ and $\mu$ is a continuous distribution over $\mathbb {R} ^{d}$ , while $\nu =\sum _{j=1}^{J}\nu _{j}\delta _{y_{i}}$ is a discrete distribution which assigns probability mass $\nu _{j}$ to site $y_{j}\in \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ .
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] which is a finite-dimensional convex optimization problem that can be solved by standard techniques, such as gradient descent.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] In the case when $c(x,y)=|x-y|^{2}/2$ , one can show that the set of $x\in \mathbf {X}$ assigned to a particular site j is a convex polyhedron.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] The resulting configuration is called a power diagram.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] The proof of this solution appears in Galichon (2016).
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] for $\mu$ -almost all $x\in X$ for some locally Lipschitz, c -concave and maximal Kantorovich potential $\varphi$ .
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] A gradient descent formulation for the solution of the Monge–Kantorovich problem was given by Sigurd Angenent, Steven Haker, and Allen Tannenbaum.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] where, compared with the unregularized version, the "hard" constraint in the former dual ( $\varphi _{x}+\psi _{y}-c_{xy}\geq 0$ ) has been replaced by a "soft" penalization of that constraint (the sum of the $\varepsilon \exp \left((\varphi _{x}+\psi _{y}-c_{xy})/\varepsilon \right)$ terms).
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] The existence of such matrices generalizes Sinkhorn's theorem and the matrices can be computed using the Sinkhorn–Knopp algorithm, which simply consists of iteratively looking for $\varphi _{x}$ to solve **Equation 5.1**, and $\psi _{y}$ to solve **Equation 5.2**.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] Sinkhorn–Knopp's algorithm is therefore a coordinate descent algorithm on the dual regularized problem.
[src:optimal-transport/monge-problem] The Monge–Kantorovich optimal transport has found applications in wide range in different fields.
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] Compared with the original GAN discriminator, the Wasserstein GAN discriminator provides a better learning signal to the generator.
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] This allows the training to be more stable when generator is learning distributions in very high dimensional spaces.
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] The original GAN method is based on the GAN game, a zero-sum game with 2 players: generator and discriminator.
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] The game is defined over a probability space $(\Omega ,{\mathcal {B}},\mu _{ref})$ , The generator's strategy set is the set of all probability measures $\mu _{G}$ on $(\Omega ,{\mathcal {B}})$ , and the discriminator's strategy set is the set of measurable functions $D:\Omega \to [0,1]$ .
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] The objective of the game is $L(\mu _{G},D):=\mathbb {E} _{x\sim \mu _{ref}}[\ln D(x)]+\mathbb {E} _{x\sim \mu _{G}}[\ln(1-D(x))].$ The generator aims to minimize it, and the discriminator aims to maximize it.
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] where the derivative is the Radon–Nikodym derivative, and $D_{JS}$ is the Jensen–Shannon divergence.
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] Repeat the GAN game many times, each time with the generator moving first, and the discriminator moving second.
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] Each time the generator $\mu _{G}$ changes, the discriminator must adapt by approaching the ideal $D^{*}(x)={\frac {d\mu _{ref}}{d(\mu _{ref}+\mu _{G})}}.$ Since we are really interested in $\mu _{ref}$ , the discriminator function D is by itself rather uninteresting.
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] It merely keeps track of the likelihood ratio between the generator distribution and the reference distribution.
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] At equilibrium, the discriminator is just outputting ${\frac {1}{2}}$ constantly, having given up trying to perceive any difference.
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] Concretely, in the GAN game, let us fix a generator $\mu _{G}$ , and improve the discriminator step-by-step, with $\mu _{D,t}$ being the discriminator at step t .
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] Thus, we see that the point of the discriminator is mainly as a critic to provide feedback for the generator, about "how far it is from perfection", where "far" is defined as Jensen–Shannon divergence.
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] Naturally, this brings the possibility of using a different criteria of farness.
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] There are many possible divergences to choose from, such as the f-divergence family, which would give the f-GAN.
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] A proof can be found in the main page on Wasserstein metric.
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] In the Wasserstein GAN game, the discriminator provides a better gradient than in the GAN game.
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] Consider for example a game on the real line where both $\mu _{G}$ and $\mu _{ref}$ are Gaussian.
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] As shown, the generator in GAN is motivated to let its $\mu _{G}$ "slide down the peak" of $\ln(1-D(x))$ .
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] Similarly for the generator in Wasserstein GAN.
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] For Wasserstein GAN, $D_{WGAN}$ has gradient 1 almost everywhere, while for GAN, $\ln(1-D)$ has flat gradient in the middle, and steep gradient elsewhere.
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] As a result, the variance for the estimator in GAN is usually much larger than that in Wasserstein GAN.
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] The problem with $D_{JS}$ is much more severe in actual machine learning situations.
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] Consider training a GAN to generate ImageNet, a collection of photos of size 256-by-256.
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] The space of all such photos is $\mathbb {R} ^{256^{2}}$ , and the distribution of ImageNet pictures, $\mu _{ref}$ , concentrates on a manifold of much lower dimension in it.
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] Consequently, any generator strategy $\mu _{G}$ would almost surely be entirely disjoint from $\mu _{ref}$ , making $D_{JS}(\mu _{G}\|\mu _{ref})=+\infty$ .
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] Thus, a good discriminator can almost perfectly distinguish $\mu _{ref}$ from $\mu _{G}$ , as well as any $\mu _{G}'$ close to $\mu _{G}$ .
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] Thus, the gradient $\nabla _{\mu _{G}}L(\mu _{G},D)\approx 0$ , creating no learning signal for the generator.
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] Training the generator in Wasserstein GAN is just gradient descent, the same as in GAN (or most deep learning methods), but training the discriminator is different, as the discriminator is now restricted to have bounded Lipschitz norm.
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] Let the discriminator function D to be implemented by a multilayer perceptron: $D=D_{n}\circ D_{n-1}\circ \cdots \circ D_{1}$ where $D_{i}(x)=h(W_{i}x)$ , and $h:\mathbb {R} \to \mathbb {R}$ is a fixed activation function with $\sup _{x}|h'(x)|\leq 1$ .
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] For example, the hyperbolic tangent function $h=\tanh$ satisfies the requirement.
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] This is the weight clipping method, proposed by the original paper.
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] The algorithm can be further accelerated by memoization: At step t , store $x_{i}^{*}(t)$ .
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] Then at step $t+1$ , use $x_{i}^{*}(t)$ as the initial guess for the algorithm.
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] This is the spectral normalization method.
[src:optimal-transport/wasserstein-gan] The discriminator, in attempting to minimize the new loss function, would naturally bring $\nabla D(x)$ close to a everywhere, thus making $\|D\|_{L}\approx a$ .
